It’s been a challenging couple weeks here at Studio Sampou. December 3rd I was wildly bucked off a horse during a lope ride at @tanqueverderanch trail ride. It was the day after I finished a wonderful week of teaching. I was so excited to go on a trail ride however it ended in a frightening experience with painful injuries to my whole body: muscle pulls, bruised bones, back strain and my left hand now casted after bone and tendon surgery on my finger three days ago. I hope that I regain full mobility with PT commitment. I’ve got lots of healing ahead of me but here are a few interesting tidbits about this event. 1. Surgeon sewed my finger bones and tendons back together (screws not delicate enough) and secured the top of my nail with a white little button that threads my tendon to the tip right through my nail. (See closeup in reel) Bizarre and strangely amusing as a sewist/quilter. 2. My surgeon is 78 years young.  They call him the Hand Wizard among the orthopedic community of San Francisco. I’m hoping he worked his wizardry on me! Time will tell. 3. It could have been soooo much worse.  When Fergus started bucking during a fast run, within a few seconds I quickly realized he wasn’t going to let up until I was off, I tried everything to gain control of my horse to no avail. He was determined to be rid of me despite my commands and pulling of the rein. All I could think of when finally going down was please don’t trample on me. I shouted the F word about 50 times and the adrenaline was pulsing through my veins that I jumped up and stomped back to the stables in the rain. It started just a minute after I was thrown. It wasn’t until later I realized how hurt my body was and then Todd - thank goodness was there to take me to emergency in Tucson. 4. I’ve been working out at the gym, Mt biking, yoga etc (a lot!)these past two years and had I not, I know my injuries would have been worse. My body is strong and resilient and the trauma will heal.  For now I feel a bit like a lump with a stump but the holidays will just have to slow down to a first gear. I know it won’t be easy getting back on the horse. Not even sure I will. I love horseback riding but….

After being thrown from a horse…I’m Stitched, Quilted and Buttoned back together. Hand surgery was a success and my bones and tendons should heal well with lots of hand therapy and care! I’m so grateful to the medical wizards at @kpthrive Dr Johnson and my wonderful husband. Thank you for all your well wishes and your own stories. Love hearing from you and I read every word 💕🥰Meanwhile I’ve got some great help in the studio to keep us going. 2022 went out with a big  OUCH lots of f#<!s and very odd use of a button if you ask me (anchoring my tendon in place at the top of my pinky through my nail bed) and a freakin Yeee Haw. 🐴🌵🧵🪡😳

Elephant and I quilt is celebrating its 10th Anniversary as a pattern available for quilt/elephant lovers every where and  we decided to do a kit for the very first time! Only took us 10 years to get around to bundling it. Hahaha. But come February I will be returning to Thailand hand carrying this quilt to gift it to Lek Chailert at The Elephant Nature Park (ENP) in Chiang Mai Thailand. She inspired me when I met her in 2013.  I cannot wait for this special trip back to ENP. Lek is world famous for founding this award winning sanctuary. All these years we’ve been donating part of our proceeds of the sale of my little pattern to help adopt, feed and care for these beautiful animals that are so well attended to by the good people of ENP. I will be teaching this class @sistersoutdoorquiltshow July ‘23. There are a few spaces left! Namaste ❤️ My final stop on Asia tour was Nepal to trek in Langtang Valley in the Himalayas with my siblings and family. Grateful to experience it with people I love dearly. To visit Hands in Outreach girls @handsinoutreach to support young women of Kathmandu and their quest for bettering their lives. To hunt for more textile and pattern inspiration to share with you. And to finish in quiet observation of the majestic sights hiking among the highest peaks in the world. We live in a complicated world. My intent is to see as clearly as I can. To be informed, sensitive and kind. To share the beauty I seek knowing it is not always easy or obvious to find. Thank you for coming along here on Instagram. May you go in peace. Continue to hone your craft and connect with and love one another.

Hi. Late to the party of #igquiltfest2023. February was a big travel/textile exploration month in Thailand, Cambodia and Nepal. I’m just resurfacing. This photo in the Himalayas was just ten days ago with Yangjen. My #igquiltfest catchup is listed below. 
Top Ten Today. 

* I am happily STILL designing fabric and quilts 😎 It’s been 35 years! 
* In 1988 I moved from Boston to San Francisco to design surfboards…until  I met Mr Bear of P&B Textiles who made quilt fabric! Sharp right turn!
* Had it not been for a serendipitous elevator ride in Las Vegas, I may never have met Todd who has been my husband since 1995 and the light of my life. 
* Todd runs C&T Publishing and my MIL Carolie Hensley started the Cotton Patch in 1979. I’m in deep! The word “fabric” and “quilt” must have been said at least 50k times around the dinner table thus far. 
* Grew up sewing but didn’t call myself a “Real Quilter” until I made my Octagon Shimmer 
* Mom made everything from scratch. Clothing included. I’m the youngest of 5 kids. My siblings are my best friends. 🥰🥰🥰🥰🥰. They better read this and agree. 
* My three sons are sporty and not one of them know how to quilt. I’ve forgiven them but have not given up hope. 
* When I go MIA you can find me deep in nature or on a plane to Timbuktu. 
* Ombré SKY All Day. It’s the quilter’s paint palette for everything and will never ever go out of style @robertkaufman 😉
* I sew on an old Bernina I got for xmas in 1996 from my MIL. The first quilts I made are long gone or gifted. My detail programmed hawk eyes and nimble hands are my best tools

What a fantastic retreat we just had at the second annual 🌵🌶️High Desert Hues! 🌶️🌵A week with MISA in Santa Fe was full of color, learning, stretching our skills, laughter, the nature and art of Georgia O’Keeffe. All the students soared high and I am so impressed with their creative passion to push themselves into making quilts they’d never try at home. That’s what is so exciting about quilt retreats is that we come together to be bolder, braver, helping one another, sharing bits of SKY and expand our love of making…all under a New Mexico Sun! Thank you to all my students who spent this glorious week with me and to MISA for providing the space, hospitality and support.

Highlighting student Deb Payne from High Desert Hues last week in Santa Fe. She said “working with SKY is like sewing a painting!”🤩Using just three SKY Ombres in this hills piece, she did her five steps beautifully which resulted in understanding the use of color and long pieces of SKY Ombré where the fabric does a lot of the work of shading and blending. She designed, cut and sewed graceful curves and had a lovely composition all her own inspired by O’Keeffe and the southwest.  She went on to make piece number 2 and I hope she keeps us posted on her progress! What fun to see the work evolve right before our eyes. She also was a generous classmate helping her neighbor with a curve when I was with another student. Best retreat! Hope to see more of you March 2024. Signups opening soon. Happy Birthday to our best friend Indie. At 14 she goes to bed early and wakes up late. No longer obsessed with the ball we are thankful she shifted to being crazy for food instead. It keeps her motivated to get up and walk across the room to wherever we snack. Her muzzle is white and her eyes are cloudy. Her hearing is gone unless you shout. Real loud. Her nose is most stealth and a walk around Lake Cascade is more of a never ending sniff patrol that takes human patience. Her breath smells like low tide and no matter what the season, dog hair floats around the house like fairy dust. Often landing on anyone who chapsticks. For 14 years this love giving soul has brought us abundance of laughs, excitement, snuggles, licks, craziness and yes even an unplanned litter of 6 adorable puppies. Luna, one of her pups we reared, passed away during the pandemic which made us all so sad. Indie carries on and we take everyday she wakes up and wants to eat, sniff and go for a slow stroll as a gift. She still gets excited when we put a babushka on her head or clap for her(something the kids taught her) with happy barks but for the most part she is an old dog living her best life- mellow, sweet and slow. For that we are so blessed. Happy Birthday dear girl. We love you. #dogslife #familydog #chocolatelab #quiltdog #quilt #quiltlife

Teachin’ at The Patch! Sound ON! My 3 Top Tips for laying out a log cabin block with SKY
1️⃣Have all 5-15 colors stripped at 1 1/2” and pinned to design wall
2️⃣Create your block on a 24x24” batting that you will layout your block on and easily transfer to your sewing/cutting station
3️⃣This design wall process is all about having fun with ombre colors. Precision piecing of strips will be adjusted and squared up after every round once you begin the sewing and pressing. 
Happy making! Hope this helps! For more info about SKY Ombré, Kits and Patterns go to jennifersampou.com🥳 Info in bio. Also you can by the pattern @ctpublishing

The present is FEMALE! I just returned from a weekend in the desert where 500+ women gathered to mountain bike, learn how to shred better (down and up the single tracks) gather in friendship/sisterhood and enjoy the great outdoors. The camp set ups alone were as varied as the women who backed up their trucks, sprinter vans, VWs, and airstreams during set up.  It was so freaking awesome to see how capable this group was as the opening night more and more rigs moved in, laden with bike racks, portable fire pits, shade canopies and even comfy swing chairs. I’ve never witnessed an all women’s event such as this. I was blown away. I’ve been outdoorsy my whole life and must admit that even though I have lots of great skills it’s usually been the men around me who take the reins in these situations.  How refreshing to be a part of this alternate story. Empowering and joyful to say the least. My bike derailleur was fixed by Carli, I got advice on a new MIPS helmet by Kate. Amanda, a shuttle driver and Sarah the bike guide knew the local terrain like the freckles on their own faces. The knowledge was deep and the sharing of it was overflowing. It was 100% inclusive for women of all shapes, colors and skill levels. A safe and welcoming space. The festival included bike demos, panel speakers, dance party night, food trucks, outdoor clothing pop ups, (REI, Smartwool, ShredMaiden, Shredly, Wild Rye etc) free beer from Sierra Nevada, plus workshops on how to navigate steep terrain and harness your body weight to take those banked turns with ease. I’ve gone on and on about mountain biking today with little to say about quilts or quilting- except they go with me (almost) everywhere. :). so thank you for learning a little bit about my alternate passion of the outdoors. If you are a quilter who also loves to ride, hike, ski, camp- I’d love to hear about your experiences here. Have a beautiful day. XX js

Buy Less, Choose Well. 
This is a perfect mantra when building your ultimate quilt fabric stash. A stash that is thoughtfully curated is so satisfying to use because you pay attention on how you grow your library of color and texture.  A great stash is one that presents many options and is timeless in application. Questions to ask yourself when buying a new fabric. 
1. Is this trendy and I won’t like it a year or two from now? 
2. Does this support other fabrics I have in my stash? 
3. Is this a good quality fabric from a reliable resource? 
4. Am I filling in gaps of pales or super darks, or certain hues so my stash isn’t one dimensional? 
5. Since I love specific colors, and buy a lot of those, have I taken the time to build the opposite color stories? 

My SKY and Chalk&Charcoal  Basics have been in print for years and continue to expand.  They are timeless, abundant color palettes from whisper lights to deep darks and all the colors in between. The quality is top notch- what you expect from Robert Kaufman Fabrics, and the prints themselves are varied from
Ombré to perfectly textural that  play well with every other fabric. When you buy my basics, your are building your stash well. And that just feels good.
